   The significance of this result is that it allows a numerical model to
   reuse the same machinery for all classes of time-integration methods
   described in this work. We also derive two classes of IMEX methods,
   one-dimensional and 3D, and show that they achieve their expected
   theoretical rates of convergence regardless of the geometry (e. g., 3D
   box or sphere) and introduce a new second-order IMEX Runge-Kutta method
   that performs better than the other second-order methods considered. We
   then compare all the IMEX methods in terms of accuracy and efficiency
   for two types of geophysical fluid dynamics problems: buoyant convection
   and inertia-gravity waves. These results show that the high-order
   time-integration methods yield better efficiency particularly when high
   levels of accuracy are desired.}},
